        <h4>Week 21</h4>
        <p><b>Baby : </b>The baby's skin resembles like that of an adult now having the four layers. Also the subcutaneous fat is deposited around neck, shoulders, kidneys and spine. This subcutaneous fat will be accountable for 5% of babies weight at birth. The brown fat is very much needed for baby after birth to regulate the temperature of the body.</p>
        <p>This week, your baby is making more sense of the world and developed her sense of touch. In fact your little one's grip is quite strong now, and since there is nothing else to grab in uterus. She may sometimes hold on tight to that umbilical cord. Don't worry- it's tough enough to handle it. The sense of sight is also becoming more fine-tuned your foetus can now perceive light and dark much better than before even with those fused eyelids, but remember unless you are shining a flashlight over your belly, which you can do, by the way, it will be mostly dark for your kids inside inside that cozy womb of yours.</p>
        <p>She can also hear your voice, your heart beat, gurgling stomach and whoosh whoosh of blood circulating through your body.</p>
        <p>The foetus endocrine glands are working at a full speed and the immune system is fully developed. From this week it will be joined by spleen which will produce white blood cells (leukocytes) and antibodies which will filter bacteria, protozoa and foreign bodies. leukocytes in blood will help fight off infections.</p>
        <p>During night when the foetus is more active you can try coming then buy by soothing words, soft music and lullabies.</p>
        <p><b>Mom : </b>At 21 weeks pregnant your baby might be starting to leave his mark in the form of stretch marks that is all over your stomach, butt, thighs, hips and breasts. This pink, red, purple, redish brown or dark brown streaks appear as your body expands and your tummy and breast just keep on growing, the supporting tissue under your skin gets torned and the skin stretches. Estimates vary, but at least one in two women get them, though you are likely candidate if your mom had stretch marks during her pregnancy. Rapid weight gain can also predispose you to getting stretch marks another good reason to add your pounds slowly and steadily at an average of about a pound a week these days. Depending on your complexion and the jeans you inherited, this lines first show up as red, pink or brown streaks and with time will eventually fade.</p>
        <p>Now that you are starting to look pregnant- and not just like you eat a particularly larger lunch- and those kids can no longer be mistaken for gas the reality of pregnancy is probably beginning to sink in.</p>
        <p>And with it, visit you may find, a few ambivalent or anxious feelings your even ambivalent about admitting: me, a mom?. At some point in pregnancy and usually once that pregnancy becomes a very visible reality just about every expectant mother and father begins to feel anxiety and fear almost as if you are on a runway train and there is an enormous changes coming around the bend.</p>
        <p>And not only is it completely normal to feel anxious , it's especially healthy to acknowledge it. Talk your feelings over with your friends who have had babies, they will reassure you. Most important discuss your fears with your partner's who is probably just as in need of a good heart to heart.</p>

        <p><b>Tips</b></p>
        <p><b>Raise your feet : </b>Your shoes might not be fitting you as your ankles and feet are swollen. Because your body is about 50% more blood and fluid than it did pre baby this body parts mein spell so be sure to  elevate your legs while your sit.</p>
        <p><b>Watch your weight : </b>How much weight is too much? That all depends ask your practitioner the target weight gain and then gain weight accordingly. being too plumpy or gaining access amount of weight is not good at all for you and for your baby.</p>
        <p><b>Exercise : </b>You should exercise but keep it low impact with yoga, walking or swimming. You are more susceptible to injury right now thanks to ligament loosening relaxin in your body.</p>
        <p><b>Avoid empty calories : </b>The emphasis is on "useless" (aka- empty)-you still want to eat enough of the right kinds of calories to keep your baby fed and growing. After all the idea is not to lose weight. Losing weight is always a bad idea when you are pregnant but to slow the rate at which you are gaining. Easy, nutritious ,calorie reducing strategy strategies like substituting fresh fruit for dried baked potatoes or yams for French French fries can make a big difference.</p>
        <p><b>Walk 30 minutes : </b>Both during pregnancy and in those first postpartum weeks physical activity is one of the best ways to stimulate your bowels and fight constipation. Even just half hour walk a day can do the trick especially if you drink plenty of water and favour fibre rich foods just remember to take some trail mix when you hit the trail.</p>
        <p><b>Hair removal : </b>Use a plucker or a razor to shave an area with unwanted hairs. If your skin is not so sensitive you can go for waxing too but no laser, electrolysis ,depilatories and bleaching.</p>

